#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:1
msgid "Additions to the prelude"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:3
msgid ""
"🚧 The 2024 Edition has not yet been released and hence this section is "
"still \"under construction\". More information may be found in the tracking "
"issue at <https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/121042>."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:6
msgid "Summary"
msgstr "摘要"

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:8
msgid ""
"The [`Future`](../../std/future/trait.Future.html) and [`IntoFuture`](../../"
"std/future/trait.IntoFuture.html) traits are now part of the prelude."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:9
msgid ""
"This might make calls to trait methods ambiguous which could make some code "
"fail to compile."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:10
msgid ""
"`RustcEncodable` and `RustcDecodable` have been removed from the prelude."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:15
msgid "Details"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:17
msgid ""
"The [prelude of the standard library](../../std/prelude/index.html) is the "
"module containing everything that is automatically imported in every module. "
"It contains commonly used items such as `Option`, `Vec`, `drop`, and `Clone`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:20
msgid ""
"The Rust compiler prioritizes any manually imported items over those from "
"the prelude, to make sure additions to the prelude will not break any "
"existing code. For example, if you have a crate or module called `example` "
"containing a `pub struct Option;`, then `use example::*;` will make `Option` "
"unambiguously refer to the one from `example`; not the one from the standard "
"library."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:26
msgid ""
"However, adding a _trait_ to the prelude can break existing code in a subtle "
"way. For example, a call to `x.poll()` which comes from a `MyPoller` trait "
"might fail to compile if `std`'s `Future` is also imported, because the call "
"to `poll` is now ambiguous and could come from either trait."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:29
msgid ""
"As a solution, Rust 2024 will use a new prelude. It's identical to the "
"current one, except for the following changes:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:32
msgid "Added:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:33
msgid "[`std::future::Future`](../../std/future/trait.Future.html)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:34
msgid "[`std::future::IntoFuture`](../../std/future/trait.IntoFuture.html)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:35
msgid "Removed:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:36
msgid "`RustcEncodable`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:37
msgid "`RustcDecodable`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:39
msgid "`RustcEncodable` and `RustcDecodable` removal"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:41
msgid ""
"`RustcEncodable` and `RustcDecodable` are two undocumented derive macros "
"that have been removed from the prelude. These were deprecated before Rust "
"1.0, but remained within the standard library prelude. The 2024 Edition has "
"removed these from the prelude since they are not expected to be used."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2024/prelude.md:45
msgid ""
"If in the unlikely case there is a project still using these, it is "
"recommended to switch to a serialization library, such as those found on "
"[crates.io](https://crates.io/categories/encoding)."
msgstr ""

